data.content:
## Migration Analysis

Your code has **four** Thread.Abort patterns that need replacement:

| Pattern | Location | Replacement |
|---|---|---|
| Cancellable work loop | `while (_running)` | `CancellationToken` |
| ThreadAbortException as control flow | `catch` block with `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| Thread.ResetAbort | Prevents rethrow so `finally` runs | Remove — `OperationCanceledException` doesn't auto-rethrow |
| Blocking call interruption | `GetNextItem()` may block | Pass token to unblock it |
| Force stop via `Thread.Abort()` | `Stop()` method | `CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()` |

## Migrated Code (.NET 8)

```csharp
public class BackgroundProcessor : IDisposable
{
    private Thread? _workerThread;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        var token = _cts.Token;
        _workerThread = new Thread(() => ProcessLoop(token));
        _workerThread.IsBackground = true;
        _workerThread.Start();
    }

    private void ProcessLoop(CancellationToken token)
    {
        while (!token.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            try
            {
                // Pass the token so blocking calls can be interrupted cooperatively.
                var item = GetNextItem(token);
                ProcessItem(item, token);
            }
            catch (OperationCanceledException) when (token.IsCancellationRequested)
            {
                // Cancellation was requested — clean up partial work.
                RollbackCurrentTransaction();
                // No ResetAbort needed: OperationCanceledException does NOT
                // auto-rethrow, so the finally block runs normally and the
                // loop condition will exit on the next iteration.
            }
            finally
            {
                FlushBuffers();
            }
        }
    }

    public void Stop()
    {
        if (_cts is null) return;

        _cts.Cancel(); // signal cooperative cancellation

        // Wait up to 2 seconds for the thread to finish cleanly.
        // Thread.Join replaces the old Thread.Sleep + Abort pattern.
        if (_workerThread is not null && _workerThread.IsAlive)
        {
            if (!_workerThread.Join(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(2)))
            {
                // Thread didn't stop in time. With cooperative cancellation
                // this means GetNextItem/ProcessItem isn't checking the token.
                // Log a warning — there is NO equivalent to Thread.Abort in
                // modern .NET. Fix the blocking call to respect the token.
                Console.Error.WriteLine(
                    "Warning: worker thread did not stop within timeout.");
            }
        }
    }

    public void Dispose()
    {
        Stop();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = null;
    }
}
```

## What Must Change in `GetNextItem`

This is the **most critical** part. If `GetNextItem()` blocks (e.g., on a queue or I/O), it **must** accept and respect the token — otherwise cancellation stalls:

```csharp
// BEFORE — blocks indefinitely, only Thread.Abort could interrupt it
private Item GetNextItem()
{
    return _queue.Take(); // blocks until an item is available
}

// AFTER — wakes up when cancellation is requested
private Item GetNextItem(CancellationToken token)
{
    return _queue.Take(token); // throws OperationCanceledException on cancel
}
```

If you're using `Thread.Sleep` anywhere in the blocking path:

```csharp
// BEFORE
Thread.Sleep(1000);

// AFTER — wakes immediately on cancellation
token.WaitHandle.WaitOne(1000);
```

## Key Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| **Not passing token to `GetNextItem`** | The thread stays blocked forever — `Cancel()` has no effect. This is the #1 migration failure. |
| **Not passing token through the full call chain** | If `ProcessItem` calls sub-methods that block, they all need the token too. |
| **Expecting `Cancel()` to be immediate** | Cooperative cancellation only fires at the next checkpoint. Add `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` between expensive operations inside `ProcessItem`. |
| **Forgetting to dispose `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks timers and callbacks. The `IDisposable` pattern above handles this. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | The `when (token.IsCancellationRequested)` filter ensures you only catch *your* cancellation, not an unrelated one from a nested call. |
| **Removing cleanup logic when removing the catch block** | The `RollbackCurrentTransaction()` call was critical — it's preserved in the new `catch (OperationCanceledException)` block. |

## Paradigm Shift Summary

```
.NET Framework (preemptive)          →  .NET 8 (cooperative)
─────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
Thread.Abort()                       →  CancellationTokenSource.Cancel()
catch (ThreadAbortException)         →  catch (OperationCanceledException)
Thread.ResetAbort()                  →  Remove (not needed)
_running volatile bool               →  CancellationToken.IsCancellationRequested
Thread.Sleep + Abort as timeout      →  Thread.Join(timeout) + log warning
Blocking call interrupted by Abort   →  Pass CancellationToken to blocking call
```

The fundamental change: in .NET Framework, the *runtime* could forcibly inject an exception into any thread. In .NET 8, the *code itself* must check for cancellation and voluntarily stop. Every blocking call in your pipeline needs to accept a `CancellationToken`.
